      "message": "The reason I went with this approach is to ensure our code functions regardless of user input. There are only 2 cases where timeout before any reading/writing should be possible:\n\n1) If the mutex takes a long time to acquire. With the planned design, this should never happen, but if this is the concern I can change to a timed_mutex rather than a lock_guard (and return immediately if timed_mutex::try_lock_for(timeout) fails)\n\n2) If timeout is very small (ie timeout \u003d 0). In this case, we probably can expect all calls to PerformNetworkingOperations() will do no reads/writes (because we always expect this method called with the same timeout every time). In this case, we will never actually read/write any data and the thread will starve\nIf we want our code to continue to function in this case (our SocketHandleWaiter code does function as-is with timeout \u003d 0), then we need to do at least one read or write per iteration.\n\nWhat do you think?",
